While Kenya’s population has grown steadily over the years, agricultural output has stagnated. The country has three distinct land tenure regimes: government-owned, trust and freehold. Some 10 per cent of the land is owned by government. Trust land accounts for some 70 per cent, while 20 per cent is freehold.
Private freehold is held by individuals, groups of individuals, and private corporate persons. Collective freehold land includes group ranches established under the Land (Group Representatives) Act of 1968. The government has the authority to extinguish or restrict property rights over land and natural resources, including the power to limit the use of privately held land for national interests.



