In Kenya, public land has potential opportunity to lead, shape, or unlock development. The national and county governments should consider how best to use idle public land to generate economic growth and employment.
Public-private-partnership (PPP) frameworks have demonstrated a win-win approach when it comes to infrastructural development as well as the energy sector. This approach can also be considered when it comes to solving the unemployment challenge.
An excellent place to start would be the use of lease-hold agreements with the private sector players in need of land if the resultant product of the land-use is economic development.
This way, the land would still belong to the government at the end of the day and can be allocated to others after the tenure lapses.
